# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: clan-bruce
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:clan-bruce/airth-castle] According to an account attributed to Blind Harry, in 1298 William Wallace attacked a previous wooden fortification on this site to rescue his imprisoned uncle, a priest from Dunipace.
[src:clan-bruce/airth-castle] A later castle was burnt or destroyed after the defeat of King James III at Sauchieburn in 1488, and Robert Bruce of Airth was given £100 Scots towards rebuilding.
[src:clan-bruce/airth-castle] The southwest tower is the earliest part, dating to the period immediately thereafter.
[src:clan-bruce/airth-castle] An extension was added on the east side in the mid 16th century.
[src:clan-bruce/airth-castle] Mary Bruce, a daughter of the laird of Airth, was a companion of Mary, Queen of Scots in England.
[src:clan-bruce/airth-castle] The family were Jacobite sympathizers who were forced to sell after the failure of the 1715 rising.
[src:clan-bruce/airth-castle] The castle is a major historic building that retains much medieval fabric.
[src:clan-bruce/airth-castle] As such, Historic Environment Scotland has designated it a Category A listed building.
[src:clan-bruce/airth-castle] The ruins of the former parish church of Airth are within the grounds.
[src:clan-bruce/airth-castle] Airth Castle is owned by Airth Castle Limited and was operated by Airth Castle Hotel & Spa, a company formed in 2004.
[src:clan-bruce/airth-castle] The operator entered administration and ceased trading in March 2023.
[src:clan-bruce/airth-castle] Parts of the Airth Castle Hotel building were destroyed when a fire broke out during the early hours of 23 September 2024.
[src:clan-bruce/airth-castle] The castle, like many in the area, has a variety of ghostlore stories associated with it.
[src:clan-bruce/alastair-bruce-of-crionaich] Major-General **Alastair Andrew Bernard Reibey Bruce of Crionaich** CB OBE TD VR DL (born 25 June 1960), is a British television journalist and former senior officer in the British Army Reserves who served as Governor of Edinburgh Castle from 2019 until 2024.
[src:clan-bruce/alastair-bruce-of-crionaich] Royal, Religious and National Events Commentator for Sky News, Bruce was previously engaged by the BBC, and was historical adviser to several feature films and the ITV series *Downton Abbey*.
[src:clan-bruce/alastair-bruce-of-crionaich] Bruce commanded the TA Media Operations Group before his appointment as Governor of Edinburgh Castle and continues to serve as an officer of arms in the Royal Household.
[src:clan-bruce/alastair-bruce-of-crionaich] Alastair Andrew Bernard Reibey Bruce was born on 25 June 1960 in Winchester, Hampshire, England, the younger son of Lieutenant Commander Henry Victor Bruce of Salloch and Helen Vernon Wallop *née* William-Powlett, daughter and co-heiress of Vice Admiral Sir Peveril William-Powlett.
[src:clan-bruce/alastair-bruce-of-crionaich] His great-grandfather was the 8th Earl of Elgin.
[src:clan-bruce/alastair-bruce-of-crionaich] Brought up in Hampshire, he spent much of his childhood in Sutherland, in the far north of the Scottish Highlands, where his parents owned the Sallachy Estate near the village of Lairg.
[src:clan-bruce/alastair-bruce-of-crionaich] Bruce was educated at Milton Abbey School, an independent boarding school for boys (now co-educational), in Milton Abbas, Dorset, before attending the Royal Military Academy Sandhurst in Berkshire.
[src:clan-bruce/alastair-bruce-of-crionaich] Commissioned in the British Army, in 1979, Bruce was promoted, the following year, to lieutenant in the 2nd Battalion of the Scots Guards.
[src:clan-bruce/alastair-bruce-of-crionaich] He served as a regular officer for four years, seeing active service in the Falklands War of 1982.
[src:clan-bruce/alastair-bruce-of-crionaich] The following year, he erected a cairn at Sallachy in Sutherland, in memory of his orderly in the Falklands, Guardsman James Reynolds, from the village of Bridge of Weir in Renfrewshire, who was killed in action while rescuing a wounded comrade, who survived.
[src:clan-bruce/alastair-bruce-of-crionaich] Reynolds died at the age of 19 at Tumbledown Mountain, then being the only soldier to be awarded the Distinguished Conduct Medal posthumously.
[src:clan-bruce/alastair-bruce-of-crionaich] At the time, Lieutenant Bruce said: "On returning to Britain after the Falklands, I decided I wanted to do something in honour of Jim Reynolds.
[src:clan-bruce/alastair-bruce-of-crionaich] He was such a brave young man who was well-liked by everyone".
[src:clan-bruce/alastair-bruce-of-crionaich] An Assistant Vice-President with Merrill Lynch from 1983 to 1989, Bruce remained a military reservist.
[src:clan-bruce/alastair-bruce-of-crionaich] In 2004, he took command of the reserve unit, Media Operations Group, co-ordinating media representation of military activity.
[src:clan-bruce/alastair-bruce-of-crionaich] In the same year, he was mobilised on active operations in Iraq, serving in Operation TELIC.
[src:clan-bruce/alastair-bruce-of-crionaich] He was promoted Colonel in the Territorial Army, and became the equerry to Prince Edward.
[src:clan-bruce/alastair-bruce-of-crionaich] He accompanied HRH the Earl of Wessex to events such as the Wedding of Albert II, Prince of Monaco, and Charlene Wittstock.
[src:clan-bruce/alastair-bruce-of-crionaich] After serving as Director of Ceremonies of the Order of St John, in 2008, Bruce was appointed a Knight of St John (OStJ (1991); CStJ (1997)), and in 2010, became an Officer of the Order of the British Empire in the Queen's Birthday Honours for "services to the Territorial Army".
[src:clan-bruce/alastair-bruce-of-crionaich] He was Deputy Commander of 3rd Division and Colonel of the London Scottish Regiment.
[src:clan-bruce/alastair-bruce-of-crionaich] In 2019, Bruce succeeded Major General Michael Riddell-Webster as Governor of Edinburgh Castle and was promoted to the rank of major general.
[src:clan-bruce/alastair-bruce-of-crionaich] In 2020, Bruce was appointed Honorary Colonel of 5 Military Intelligence Battalion; and in 2021, as Honorary Colonel of Tayforth Universities Officers' Training Corps.
[src:clan-bruce/alastair-bruce-of-crionaich] He was further appointed Honorary Colonel of the 6th Battalion The Royal Regiment of Scotland Army Reserve from 1 December 2023.
[src:clan-bruce/alastair-bruce-of-crionaich] Bruce was appointed a Deputy Lieutenant for Greater London on 9 October 2012, and a Deputy Lieutenant of Hampshire in March 2026.
[src:clan-bruce/alastair-bruce-of-crionaich] Bruce was appointed a Companion of the Order of the Bath (CB) in the 2025 New Year Honours.
[src:clan-bruce/alastair-bruce-of-crionaich] Queen Elizabeth II appointed Bruce as one of her heralds on 7 October 1998 as Fitzalan Pursuivant, and he has served as a member of the Royal Company of Archers, the Sovereign's ceremonial bodyguard in Scotland, since 1990.
[src:clan-bruce/alastair-bruce-of-crionaich] He also advised on the minutiae of early 20th-century society protocol, in such subjects as dress, posture, the serving of food and even on matters that might initially appear trivial, such as the use of vocabulary or the correct way to step out of a car.
[src:clan-bruce/alastair-bruce-of-crionaich] Bruce has written many books, and worked with several independent production companies in the preparation of television documentaries which are regularly aired on the BBC, America's PBS network, Discovery Channel and A&E channels.
[src:clan-bruce/alastair-bruce-of-crionaich] Among these are *Nicholas and Alexandra*, *Victoria and Albert* (2001) and *Days of Majesty*.
[src:clan-bruce/alastair-bruce-of-crionaich] In 2017, Bruce recorded a conversation with Queen Elizabeth II for the BBC: the Queen spoke about her coronation, more than 60 years earlier, in a programme entitled *The Coronation*.
[src:clan-bruce/alastair-bruce-of-crionaich] Bruce has lectured widely throughout Britain, Europe and the United States; his subjects range from the last Tsars of Russia to British monarchy and the Vatican.
[src:clan-bruce/alastair-bruce-of-crionaich] In 2011, he was appointed Honorary Professor of Media at the University of Winchester.
[src:clan-bruce/alastair-bruce-of-crionaich] In 2024, Bruce unsuccessfully ran for election as Chancellor of Oxford University.
[src:clan-bruce/alastair-bruce-of-crionaich] The Bruce family funds the Lieutenant Commander Henry V Bruce Award for Hampshire Scouts which rewards inspirational young people in scouting, because of Lieutenant Commander Bruce's long term association with Hampshire Scouts.
[src:clan-bruce/alastair-bruce-of-crionaich] Bruce is also a Hampshire Scouts ambassador.
[src:clan-bruce/alastair-bruce-of-crionaich] Recognised in the name of **Bruce of Crionaich** by Lord Lyon King of Arms in 1984, on 3 July 2021, after 20 years together, Bruce was married to Stephen Knott at St John's Episcopal Church by the Bishop of Edinburgh.
[src:clan-bruce/alastair-bruce-of-crionaich] Bruce is a godfather to James, Earl of Wessex, the only son of the Duke and Duchess of Edinburgh.
[src:clan-bruce/alastair-bruce-of-crionaich] As an Equerry to the Duke of Edinburgh (formerly the Earl of Wessex) since 2004, Bruce wears an aiguillette on his right shoulder while in military uniform, as well the Royal Cypher of the Duke of Edinburgh on his epaulettes.
[src:clan-bruce/alastair-bruce-of-crionaich] As a Deputy Lieutenant from 2012, he is entitled to use the post-nominal letters "DL" in perpetuity.
[src:clan-bruce/alastair-bruce-of-crionaich] He earned the Territorial Decoration (TD) in 2004.
[src:clan-bruce/alastair-bruce-of-crionaich] The medal was awarded retrospectively in 2026.
[src:clan-bruce/alexander-bruce-2nd-earl-of-kincardine] His grandfather, Sir George Bruce had built up a fortune in coal-mining and salt-production, building Culross Palace in Fife in 1597.
[src:clan-bruce/alexander-bruce-2nd-earl-of-kincardine] During the English Civil War he served as a captain with the Royalist cavalry, fighting at the Battle of Worcester.
[src:clan-bruce/alexander-bruce-2nd-earl-of-kincardine] He was a probably a participant in Glencairn's uprising, after which he was briefly imprisoned.
[src:clan-bruce/alexander-bruce-2nd-earl-of-kincardine] For the latter part of Cromwell's Commonwealth he lived in Bremen in voluntary exile.
[src:clan-bruce/alexander-bruce-2nd-earl-of-kincardine] In 1659 he married Veronica, a sister of Cornelis van Aerssen van Sommelsdijck and delivered stone for the construction of the townhall of Amsterdam.
[src:clan-bruce/alexander-bruce-2nd-earl-of-kincardine] He returned to Scotland once Charles II was restored to the English throne.
[src:clan-bruce/alexander-bruce-2nd-earl-of-kincardine] He inherited the family estates in Culross on the death of his brother in 1662, although had been managing them for some time before that due to his brother's incapacity.
[src:clan-bruce/alexander-bruce-2nd-earl-of-kincardine] He resumed mining activities at Culross Colliery sinking the Ding Dong Pit and probably the Valleyfield Moat Pit.
[src:clan-bruce/alexander-bruce-2nd-earl-of-kincardine] He was granted a 21-year monopoly for the export of stone from Scotland in 1662.
[src:clan-bruce/alexander-bruce-2nd-earl-of-kincardine] On 20 June 1667 Bruce is listed as a Treasurer of Scotland.
[src:clan-bruce/alexander-bruce-2nd-earl-of-kincardine] In the same year he was an Extraordinary Lord of Session.
[src:clan-bruce/alexander-bruce-2nd-earl-of-kincardine] Bruce was one those making up the 1660 committee of 12 that led to formation of the Royal Society of London, and he conducted extensive correspondence with fellow freemason Sir Robert Moray.
[src:clan-bruce/alexander-bruce-2nd-earl-of-kincardine] These letters are the main source of biographical information on Bruce.
[src:clan-bruce/alexander-iii-of-scotland] Alexander was born at Roxburgh, the only son of Alexander II by his second wife, Marie de Coucy.
[src:clan-bruce/alexander-iii-of-scotland] His father died on 6 July 1249 and he became king at the age of seven, inaugurated at Scone on 13 July 1249.
[src:clan-bruce/alexander-iii-of-scotland] The years of his minority featured an embittered struggle for the control of affairs between two rival parties, the one led by Walter Comyn, Earl of Menteith, the other by Alan Durward, Justiciar of Scotia.
[src:clan-bruce/alexander-iii-of-scotland] The former dominated the early years of Alexander's reign.
[src:clan-bruce/alexander-iii-of-scotland] At the marriage of Alexander to Margaret of England in 1251, Henry III of England seized the opportunity to demand homage from his son-in-law for the Scottish kingdom, but Alexander did not comply.
[src:clan-bruce/alexander-iii-of-scotland] In 1255 an interview between the English and Scottish kings at Kelso led to Menteith and his party losing to Durward's party.
[src:clan-bruce/alexander-iii-of-scotland] However, although disgraced, they still retained great influence, and two years later, seizing the person of the King, they compelled their rivals to consent to the establishment of a regency representative of both parties.
[src:clan-bruce/alexander-iii-of-scotland] On attaining his majority at the age of 21 in 1262, Alexander declared his intention to resume the projects on the Western Isles which the death of his father thirteen years before had cut short.
[src:clan-bruce/alexander-iii-of-scotland] He laid a formal claim before King Haakon IV of Norway.
[src:clan-bruce/alexander-iii-of-scotland] Haakon rejected the claim, and in the following year, responded with a formidable invasion.
[src:clan-bruce/alexander-iii-of-scotland] Sailing around the west coast of Scotland, he halted off the Isle of Arran, and negotiations commenced.
[src:clan-bruce/alexander-iii-of-scotland] Alexander artfully prolonged the talks until the autumn storms began.
[src:clan-bruce/alexander-iii-of-scotland] At length Haakon, weary of delay, attacked, only to encounter a terrific storm which greatly damaged his ships.
[src:clan-bruce/alexander-iii-of-scotland] The Battle of Largs on 2 October 1263 proved indecisive, but even so, Haakon's position was hopeless.
[src:clan-bruce/alexander-iii-of-scotland] Baffled, he turned homewards, but died in Orkney on 15 December 1263.
[src:clan-bruce/alexander-iii-of-scotland] The Isles now lay at Alexander's feet, and in 1266 Haakon's successor, his son Magnus the Lawmender, concluded the Treaty of Perth, by which he ceded the Isle of Man and the Western Isles to Scotland in return for monetary payments.
[src:clan-bruce/alexander-iii-of-scotland] Norway retained Orkney and Shetland until 1469, when they became a dowry for James III's bride, Margaret of Denmark.
[src:clan-bruce/alexander-iii-of-scotland] Alexander had married Margaret of England, daughter of King Henry III of England and Eleanor of Provence, on 26 December 1251, when he was ten years old and she was eleven.
[src:clan-bruce/alexander-iii-of-scotland] David (20 March 1272 – June 1281 Stirling Castle), buried in Dunfermline Abbey.
[src:clan-bruce/alexander-iii-of-scotland] Towards the end of Alexander's reign, the death of all three of his children within a few years made the question of the succession one of pressing importance.
[src:clan-bruce/alexander-iii-of-scotland] In 1284, he induced the Estates to recognise as his heir presumptive his granddaughter, Margaret, Maid of Norway.
[src:clan-bruce/alexander-iii-of-scotland] The need for a male heir led him to contract a second marriage to Yolande of Dreux on 1 November 1285.
[src:clan-bruce/alexander-iii-of-scotland] Alexander died in a fall from his horse while riding in the dark to visit the Queen at Kinghorn in Fife on 19 March 1286 because it was her birthday the next day.
[src:clan-bruce/alexander-iii-of-scotland] He had spent the evening at Edinburgh Castle celebrating his second marriage and overseeing a meeting with royal advisers.
[src:clan-bruce/alexander-iii-of-scotland] He was cautioned against making the journey to Fife because of weather conditions but crossed the River Forth from Dalmeny to Inverkeithing anyway.
[src:clan-bruce/alexander-iii-of-scotland] On arriving in Inverkeithing, he insisted on not stopping for the night, despite the pleas of the nobles accompanying him and one of the burgesses of the town, Alexander Le Saucier.
[src:clan-bruce/alexander-iii-of-scotland] Le Saucier (who was either linked to the King's kitchen or the master of the local saltpans) must have been known to the King, since his rather blunt warning to the King lacks the usual deference: "My lord, what are you doing out in such weather and darkness?
[src:clan-bruce/alexander-iii-of-scotland] However, Alexander ignored the repeated warnings about travelling in a storm and set off with his retinue and two local guides.
[src:clan-bruce/alexander-iii-of-scotland] The king became separated from his party near Kinghorn, and was found dead with a broken neck near the shore the following morning.
[src:clan-bruce/alexander-iii-of-scotland] It is assumed that his horse lost its footing in the dark.
[src:clan-bruce/alexander-iii-of-scotland] As Alexander left no surviving children, the heir to the throne was his unborn child by Queen Yolande.
[src:clan-bruce/alexander-iii-of-scotland] When Yolande's pregnancy ended, probably with a miscarriage, Alexander's three-year-old granddaughter, Margaret, Maid of Norway, became the heir.
[src:clan-bruce/alexander-iii-of-scotland] Margaret died, still uncrowned, on her way to Scotland in 1290.
[src:clan-bruce/alexander-iii-of-scotland] The inauguration of John Balliol as King on 30 November 1292 ended the six years of the Guardians of Scotland governing the land.
[src:clan-bruce/alexander-iii-of-scotland] In 1886, a monument to Alexander III was erected at the approximate location of his death in Kinghorn.
[src:clan-bruce/alexander-iii-of-scotland] This was, in tradition, an omen of death.
[src:clan-bruce/alexander-iii-of-scotland] A similar account is given in Walter Bower's *Scotichronicon*, a figure that "seemed to glide like a ghost rather than walk on feet" supposedly appeared amidst a group performing Scottish sword dances.
[src:clan-bruce/alexander-iii-of-scotland] Alexander III has been depicted in historical novels.
[src:clan-bruce/andrew-bruce-11th-earl-of-elgin] Elgin was born in 1924 at the family seat, Broomhall House, in Fife, the eldest son of the 10th Earl of Elgin and Katherine Elizabeth, Countess of Elgin, daughter of the 1st Baron Cochrane of Cults.
[src:clan-bruce/andrew-bruce-11th-earl-of-elgin] The arrival of a male heir following the births of two daughters, Lady Martha and Lady Jean, created tremendous celebration at the Broomhall estate, which included a bonfire and fireworks attended by crowds of villagers from Limekilns and Charlestown.
[src:clan-bruce/andrew-bruce-11th-earl-of-elgin] He was styled Lord Bruce from birth and christened at Broomhall on 31 March 1924 by his great-uncle Rev.
[src:clan-bruce/andrew-bruce-11th-earl-of-elgin] His five god-parents were Field Marshal Earl Haig, his uncle the Hon.
[src:clan-bruce/andrew-bruce-11th-earl-of-elgin] Thomas Cochrane, Sir Alexander Gibb; Lord Elgin's elder sister, Lady Elisabeth Babington Smith; and Lady Victoria Cavendish-Bentinck, daughter of the Duke of Portland.
[src:clan-bruce/andrew-bruce-11th-earl-of-elgin] He was educated at Eton and at Balliol College, Oxford.
[src:clan-bruce/andrew-bruce-11th-earl-of-elgin] On 12 September 1943, Bruce was commissioned as a Second Lieutenant in the 3rd (Armoured) Bn Scots Guards and was wounded during Operation Bluecoat, the breakout from Normandy in August 1944.
[src:clan-bruce/andrew-bruce-11th-earl-of-elgin] He was invalided out of the army on 24 October 1946, with the honorary rank of lieutenant.
[src:clan-bruce/andrew-bruce-11th-earl-of-elgin] On 4 April 1951, he was appointed an instructor in the Army Cadet Force, with the rank of Lieutenant.
[src:clan-bruce/andrew-bruce-11th-earl-of-elgin] In July 1963, by then the County Cadet Commandant for Fife, he was awarded the Cadet Forces Medal.
[src:clan-bruce/andrew-bruce-11th-earl-of-elgin] He resigned his commission on 19 April 1965, retaining the honorary rank of lieutenant-colonel.
[src:clan-bruce/andrew-bruce-11th-earl-of-elgin] Since 1970, he has been Colonel-in-Chief of the 31 Combat Engineer Regiment (The Elgins), and was Honorary Colonel of the 153 (Highland) Transport Regiment from 1976 to 1986.
[src:clan-bruce/andrew-bruce-11th-earl-of-elgin] Elgin has held a number of business appointments, including as President of the Scottish Amicable Life Assurance Society (1975–1994), and Chairman of the National Savings Committee for Scotland.
[src:clan-bruce/andrew-bruce-11th-earl-of-elgin] He was also President of the Royal Scottish Automobile Club.
[src:clan-bruce/andrew-bruce-11th-earl-of-elgin] He was appointed a Justice of the Peace in 1951, was Deputy Lieutenant of Fife 1955–1987, and Lord Lieutenant 1987–1999.
[src:clan-bruce/andrew-bruce-11th-earl-of-elgin] In 1980, he was appointed by Queen Elizabeth II as her Lord High Commissioner to the General Assembly of the Church of Scotland and reappointed in 1981.
[src:clan-bruce/andrew-bruce-11th-earl-of-elgin] In 1981 HM The Queen appointed him as a Knight of the Thistle.
[src:clan-bruce/andrew-bruce-11th-earl-of-elgin] He was awarded the Canadian Forces' Decoration in 1981.
[src:clan-bruce/andrew-bruce-11th-earl-of-elgin] He is a former Captain of the Royal Company of Archers and a former convenor of the Standing Council of Scottish Chiefs.
[src:clan-bruce/andrew-bruce-11th-earl-of-elgin] He was County Cadet Commandant for Fife from 1952 to 1965, Brigade President of the Boys' Brigade from 1966 to 1985, and Grand Master Mason of Scotland from 1961 to 1965.
[src:clan-bruce/andrew-bruce-11th-earl-of-elgin] He is a Freeman of Bridgetown, Regina, Saskatchewan, Port Elgin, Winnipeg, Manitoba, St.
[src:clan-bruce/andrew-bruce-11th-earl-of-elgin] Thomas, Ontario, and Moose Jaw, Saskatchewan.
[src:clan-bruce/andrew-bruce-11th-earl-of-elgin] Lord Elgin is a Past President of the Royal Caledonian Curling Club, and is the Life President of the Broomhall Curling Club.
[src:clan-bruce/andrew-bruce-11th-earl-of-elgin] He skippered the Scottish curling teams that defeated the Governor-General of Canada's teams in a series of matches in Ottawa in 1982.
[src:clan-bruce/andrew-bruce-11th-earl-of-elgin] Lord Elgin is Chief of Clan Bruce and President of the Bruce Family Organization which is the main association for members of the Bruce family.
[src:clan-bruce/andrew-bruce-11th-earl-of-elgin] The Countess of Elgin and Kincardine was the Patron of both the Royal Caledonian Ball and Edinburgh’s Queen Margaret University.
[src:clan-bruce/andrew-bruce-11th-earl-of-elgin] The Earl succeeded to the earldoms and other family titles on the death of his father in 1968.
[src:clan-bruce/andrew-bruce-11th-earl-of-elgin] The Earl celebrated his 100th birthday on the 17 February 2024.
[src:clan-bruce/andrew-bruce-11th-earl-of-elgin] He was interviewed by the BBC as part of a project to record the memories of Second World War veterans, marking the 80th anniversary of D-Day on 6 June 2024.
[src:clan-bruce/andrew-bruce-11th-earl-of-elgin] On 15 November 2024, Elgin's wife of 65 years, Victoria, Countess of Elgin, died aged 85.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] The **Angevins** (/ˈændʒɪvɪnz/; "of/from Anjou") were a royal house of French origin that ruled England, Ireland and parts of France in the 12th and early 13th centuries; its monarchs were Henry II, Richard I and John.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Henry II won control of a vast assemblage of lands in western Europe that would last for 80 years and would retrospectively be referred to as the Angevin Empire.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] As a political entity this was structurally different from the preceding Norman and subsequent Plantagenet realms.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Geoffrey of Anjou became Duke of Normandy in 1144 and died in 1151.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] In 1152, his heir, Henry, added Aquitaine by virtue of his marriage to Eleanor of Aquitaine.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] In 1189, Henry was succeeded by his third son, Richard, whose reputation for martial prowess won him the epithet "*Cœur de Lion*" or "Lionheart".
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] He was born and raised in England but spent very little time there during his adult life, perhaps as little as six months.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Despite this Richard remains an enduring iconic figure both in England and in France, and is one of very few kings of England remembered by his nickname as opposed to regnal number.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] When Richard died, his brother John – Henry's fifth and last surviving son – took the throne.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] In 1204, John lost many of the Angevins' continental territories, including Anjou, to the French crown.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] He and his successors were still recognized as dukes of Aquitaine.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] The loss of Anjou, for which the dynasty is named, and other French fiefs made John the last of the Angevin kings of England.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] However, there is no agreement among historians.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Some make no distinction between Angevins and Plantagenets while considering Henry II as the first Plantagenet king.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] From John, the dynasty continued on the throne of England and unbroken in the senior male line until the reign of Richard II before dividing into two competing cadet branches, the House of Lancaster and the House of York.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] In the 17th century, historians would use the term "Plantagenet" when describing the house.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] In addition, it is also used pertaining to Anjou, or any sovereign, government derived from this.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] As a noun, it is used for any native of Anjou or Angevin ruler.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Richard of York, 3rd Duke of York, adopted Plantagenet as his family name in the 15th century.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] *Plantegenest* (or *Plante Genest*) had been a 12th-century nickname for his ancestor Geoffrey, Count of Anjou and Duke of Normandy.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] One of many popular theories suggests the blossom of common broom, a bright yellow ("gold") flowering plant, genista in medieval Latin, as the source of the nickname.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] It is uncertain why Richard chose this specific name, although, during the Wars of the Roses, it emphasised Richard's status as Geoffrey's patrilineal descendant.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] The retrospective usage of the name for all of Geoffrey's male-line descendants was popular during the subsequent Tudor dynasty, perhaps encouraged by the further legitimacy it gave to Richard's great-grandson, Henry VIII.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] In the late 17th century, this name passed into common usage among historians.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] The Angevins descend from Geoffrey II, Count of Gâtinais and Ermengarde of Anjou.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] In 1060 this couple inherited, via cognatic kinship, the county of Anjou from an older line dating from 870 and a noble called Ingelger.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] The marriage of their great-grandson, Geoffrey V, Count of Anjou to Matilda, the only surviving legitimate child of Henry I of England, was part of a struggle for power during the tenth and eleventh centuries among the lords of Normandy, Brittany, Poitou, Blois, Maine and the kings of France.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] It was from this marriage that Geoffrey's son, Henry, inherited the claims to England, Normandy and Anjou that marks the beginning of the Angevin and Plantagenet dynasties.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] This was the third attempt by Geoffrey's father Fulk V to build a political alliance with Normandy.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] The first was by marrying his daughter Matilda to Henry's heir William Adelin, who drowned in the wreck of the *White Ship*.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Fulk then married his daughter Sibylla to William Clito, heir to Henry's older brother Robert Curthose, but Henry had the marriage annulled to avoid strengthening William's rival claim to his lands.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] As society became more prosperous and stable in the 11th century, inheritance customs developed that allowed daughters (in the absence of sons) to succeed to principalities as well as landed estates.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] The twelfth-century chronicler Ralph de Diceto noted that the counts of Anjou extended their dominion over their neighbours by marriage rather than conquest.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] The marriage of Geoffrey to the daughter of a king (and widow of an emperor) occurred in this context.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] It is unknown whether King Henry intended to make Geoffrey his heir, but it is known that the threat presented by William Clito's rival claim to the duchy of Normandy made his negotiating position very weak.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Even so, it is probable that, should the marriage be childless, King Henry would have attempted to be succeeded by one of his Norman kinsmen such as Theobald II, Count of Champagne, or Stephen of Blois, who in the event did seize King Henry's English crown.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] King Henry's great relief in 1133 at the birth of a son to the couple, described as "the heir to the Kingdom", is understandable in the light of this situation.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Following this, the birth of a second son raised the question of whether custom would be followed with the maternal inheritance passing to first born and the paternal inheritance going to his brother, Geoffrey.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] According to William of Newburgh, writing in the 1190s, the plan failed because of Geoffrey's early death in 1151.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Henry's brother Geoffrey died in 1158, too soon to receive Anjou, but not before being installed count in Nantes after Henry aided a rebellion by its citizens against their previous lord.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] The unity of Henry's assemblage of domains was largely dependent on the ruling family, influencing the opinion of most historians that this instability made it unlikely to endure.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] The French custom of partible inheritance at the time would lead to political fragmentation.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Indeed, if Henry II's sons Henry the Young King and Geoffrey of Brittany had not died young, the inheritance of 1189 would have been fundamentally altered.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Henry and Richard both planned for partition on their deaths while attempting to provide overriding sovereignty to hold the lands together.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] For example, in 1173 and 1183, Henry tried to force Richard to acknowledge allegiance to his older brother for the duchy of Aquitaine, and later Richard would confiscate Ireland from John.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] This was complicated by the Angevins being subjects of the kings of France, who felt these feudal rights of homage and the right of allegiance more legally belonged to them.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] This was particularly true when the wardship of Geoffrey's son Arthur and lordship of Brittany was contended between 1202 and 1204.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Upon the Young King's death in 1183, Richard became heir in chief, but refused to give up Aquitaine to give John an inheritance.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] More by accident than design this meant that, while Richard inherited the patrimony, John would become lord of Ireland and Arthur would be duke of Brittany.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] By the mid-thirteenth century, there was a clear unified patrimony and Plantagenet empire but this cannot be called an *Angevin Empire* as by this date Anjou and most of the continental lands had been lost.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Henry I of England named his daughter Matilda heir; but when he died in 1135 Matilda was far from England in Anjou or Maine, while her cousin Stephen was closer in Boulogne, giving him the advantage he needed to race to England and have himself crowned and anointed king of England.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Matilda's husband Geoffrey, though he had little interest in England, commenced a long struggle for the duchy of Normandy.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] To create a second front, Matilda landed in England during 1139 to challenge Stephen, instigating the civil war known as the Anarchy.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] In 1141, she captured Stephen at the battle of Lincoln, prompting the collapse of his support.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] While Geoffrey pushed on with the conquest of Normandy over the next four years, Matilda threw away her position through arrogance and inability to be magnanimous in victory.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] She was even forced to release Stephen in a hostage exchange for her half-brother Robert, 1st Earl of Gloucester, allowing Stephen to resume control of much of England.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Geoffrey never visited England to offer practical assistance, but instead sent Henry as a male figurehead—beginning in 1142 when Henry was only 9—with a view that if England was conquered it would be Henry that would become king.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] In 1150, Geoffrey also transferred the title of Duke of Normandy to Henry but retained the dominant role in governance.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Henry faced many challenges to secure possession of his father's and grandfathers' lands that required the reassertion and extension of old suzerainties.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] In 1162 Theobald, Archbishop of Canterbury, died, and Henry saw an opportunity to re-establish what he saw as his rights over the church in England by appointing his friend Thomas Becket to succeed him.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Instead, Becket proved to be an inept politician whose defiance alienated the king and his counsellors.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Henry and Becket clashed repeatedly: over church tenures, Henry's brother's marriage and taxation.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Henry reacted by getting Becket, and other members of the English episcopate, to recognise sixteen ancient customs—governing relations between the king, his courts, and the church—in writing for the first time in the Constitutions of Clarendon.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] When Becket tried to leave the country without permission, Henry attempted to ruin him by laying a number of suits relating to Becket's time as chancellor.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] In response Becket fled into exile for five years.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Relations later improved, allowing Becket's return, but soured again when Becket saw the coronation of Henry's son as coregent by the Archbishop of York as a challenge to his authority and excommunicated those who had offended him.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Within Christian Europe Henry was widely considered complicit in Becket's death.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] The opinion of this transgression against the church made Henry a pariah, so in penance he walked barefoot into Canterbury Cathedral where he was scourged by monks.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] In 1171, Henry invaded Ireland to assert his overlordship following alarm at the success of knights that he had allowed to recruit soldiers in England and Wales, who had assumed the role of colonisers and accrued autonomous power, including Strongbow.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Pope Adrian IV had given Henry a papal blessing to expand his power into Ireland to reform the Irish church.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Originally, this would have allowed some territory to be granted to Henry's brother, William, but other matters had distracted Henry and William was now dead.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Instead, Henry's designs were made plain when he gave the lordship of Ireland to his youngest son, John.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] In 1172, Henry II tried to give his landless youngest son John a wedding gift of the three castles of Chinon, Loudun and Mirebeau.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] This angered the 18-year-old Young King, who had yet to receive any lands from his father, and prompted a rebellion by Henry II's wife and three eldest sons.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Louis VII supported the rebellion to destabilise Henry II.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] William the Lion and other subjects of Henry II also joined the revolt and it took 18 months for Henry to force the rebels to submit to his authority.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] In Le Mans in 1182, Henry II gathered his children to plan a partible inheritance in which his eldest son (also called Henry) would inherit England, Normandy and Anjou; Richard the Duchy of Aquitaine; Geoffrey Brittany, and John Ireland.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] The younger Henry rebelled again before he died of dysentery and, in 1186, Geoffrey died after a tournament accident.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] In 1189, Richard and Philip II of France took advantage of Henry's failing health and forced him to accept humiliating peace terms, including naming Richard as his sole heir.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Two days later, the old king died, defeated and miserable in the knowledge that even his favoured son John had rebelled.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] This fate was seen as the price he paid for the murder of Beckett.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] On the day of Richard's English coronation, there was a mass slaughter of Jews, described by Richard of Devizes as a "holocaust".
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] After his coronation, Richard put the Angevin Empire's affairs in order before joining the Third Crusade to the Middle East in early 1190.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Opinions of Richard by his contemporaries varied.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] He had rejected and humiliated the king of France's sister; deposed the king of Cyprus and sold the island; insulted and refused to give spoils from the Third Crusade to Leopold V, Duke of Austria, and allegedly arranged the assassination of Conrad of Montferrat.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] His cruelty was exemplified by the massacre of 2,600 prisoners in Acre.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] However, Richard was respected for his military leadership and courtly manners.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Despite victories in the Third Crusade he failed to capture Jerusalem, retreating from the Holy Land with a small band of followers.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Richard was captured by Leopold on his return journey.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] He was transferred to Henry VI, Holy Roman Emperor, and a 25-percent tax on goods and income was required to pay his 150,000-mark ransom.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Philip II of France had overrun Normandy, while John of England controlled much of Richard's remaining lands.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] However, when Richard returned to England he forgave John and re-established his control.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Leaving England permanently in 1194, Richard fought Philip for five years for the return of holdings seized during his incarceration.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] On the brink of victory, he was wounded by an arrow during the siege of Château de Châlus-Chabrol and died ten days later.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] His failure to produce an heir caused a succession crisis.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Anjou, Brittany, Maine and Touraine chose Richard's nephew Arthur as heir, while John succeeded in England and Normandy.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Philip II of France again destabilised the Plantagenet territories on the European mainland, supporting his vassal Arthur's claim to the English crown.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Eleanor supported her son John, who was victorious at the Battle of Mirebeau and captured the rebel leadership.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Arthur was murdered (allegedly by John), and his sister Eleanor would spend the rest of her life in captivity.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] John's behaviour drove a number of French barons to side with Philip, and the resulting rebellions by Norman and Angevin barons ended John's control of his continental possessions—the *de facto* end of the Angevin Empire, although Henry III would maintain his claim until 1259.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] After re-establishing his authority in England, John planned to retake Normandy and Anjou by drawing the French from Paris while another army (under Otto IV, Holy Roman Emperor) attacked from the north.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] However, his allies were defeated at the Battle of Bouvines in one of the most decisive battles in French history.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] John's nephew Otto retreated and was soon overthrown, with John agreeing to a five-year truce.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Philip's victory was crucial to the political order in England and France, and the battle was instrumental in establishing absolute monarchy in France.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] John's French defeats weakened his position in England.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] The rebellion of his English vassals resulted in *Magna Carta*, which limited royal power and established common law.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] This would form the basis of every constitutional battle of the 13th and 14th centuries.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] The barons and the crown failed to abide by *Magna Carta*, leading to the First Barons' War when rebel barons provoked an invasion by Prince Louis.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Many historians use John's death and William Marshall's appointment as protector of nine-year-old Henry III to mark the end of the Angevin period and the beginning of the Plantagenet dynasty.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Marshall won the war with victories at Lincoln and Dover in 1217, leading to the Treaty of Lambeth in which Louis renounced his claims.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] In victory, the Marshal Protectorate reissued *Magna Carta* as the basis of future government.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Historians use the period of Prince Louis's invasion to mark the end of the Angevin period and the beginning of the Plantagenet dynasty.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] The outcome of the military situation was uncertain at John's death; William Marshall saved the dynasty, forcing Louis to renounce his claim with a military victory.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] However, Philip had captured all the Angevin possessions in France except Gascony.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] This collapse had several causes, including long-term changes in economic power, growing cultural differences between England and Normandy and (in particular) the fragile, familial nature of Henry's empire.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Henry III continued his attempts to reclaim Normandy and Anjou until 1259, but John's continental losses and the consequent growth of Capetian power during the 13th century marked a "turning point in European history".
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Richard of York adopted "Plantagenet" as a family name for himself and his descendants during the 15th century.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] *Plantegenest* (or *Plante Genest*) was Geoffrey's nickname, and his emblem may have been the common broom (*planta genista* in medieval Latin).
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] It is uncertain why Richard chose the name, but it emphasised Richard's hierarchal status as Geoffrey's (and six English kings') patrilineal descendant during the Wars of the Roses.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] The retrospective use of the name for Geoffrey's male descendants was popular during the Tudor period, perhaps encouraged by the added legitimacy it gave Richard's great-grandson Henry VIII of England.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Through John, descent from the Angevins (legitimate and illegitimate) is widespread, and includes all subsequent monarchs of England and the United Kingdom.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] John also had illegitimate children with a number of mistresses, including nine sons—Richard, Oliver, John, Geoffrey, Henry, Osbert Gifford, Eudes, Bartholomew and (probably) Philip—and three daughters—Joan, Maud and (probably) Isabel.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Of these, Joan was the best known, since she married Prince Llywelyn the Great of Wales.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] The chronicler Gerald of Wales borrowed elements of the Melusine legend to give the Angevins a demonic origin, and the kings were said to tell jokes about the stories.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Henry was widely criticised by contemporaries, even in his own court.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Nevertheless, William of Newburgh, writing after his death, commented that "the experience of present evils has revived the memory of his good deeds, and the man who in his own time was hated by all men, is now declared to have been an excellent and beneficent prince".
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Henry's son Richard's contemporary image was more nuanced, since he was the first king who was also a knight.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Known as a valiant, competent and generous military leader, he was criticised by chroniclers for taxing the clergy for the Crusade and his ransom; clergy were usually exempt from taxes.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Chroniclers Richard of Devizes, William of Newburgh, Roger of Hoveden and Ralph de Diceto were generally unsympathetic to John's behaviour under Richard, but more tolerant of the earliest years of John's reign.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Accounts of the middle and later years of his reign are limited to Gervase of Canterbury and Ralph of Coggeshall, neither of whom were satisfied with John's performance as king.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] His later negative reputation was established by two chroniclers writing after the king's death: Roger of Wendover and Matthew Paris.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] The latter claimed that John attempted to convert to Islam, but this is not believed by modern historians.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Many of the changes Henry introduced during his rule had long-term consequences.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] His legal innovations form part of the basis for English law, with the Exchequer of Pleas a forerunner of the Common Bench at Westminster.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Henry's itinerant justices also influenced his contemporaries' legal reforms: Philip Augustus's creation of itinerant *bailli*, for example, drew on Henry's model.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Henry's intervention in Brittany, Wales and Scotland had a significant long-term impact on the development of their societies and governments.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] John's reign, despite its flaws, and his signing of *Magna Carta*, were seen by Whig historians as positive steps in the constitutional development of England and part of a progressive and universalist course of political and economic development in medieval England.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Winston Churchill said, "[W]hen the long tally is added, it will be seen that the British nation and the English-speaking world owe far more to the vices of John than to the labours of virtuous sovereigns".
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] *Magna Carta* was reissued by the Marshal Protectorate and later as a foundation of future government.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] The Angevins were closely associated with the Fontevraud Abbey in Anjou.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] The abbey was originally the site of his grave and those of Eleanor, Richard, his daughter Joan, grandson Raymond VII of Toulouse and John's wife—Isabella of Angoulême.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Henry III visited the abbey in 1254 to reorder these tombs and requested that his heart be buried with them.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] According to historian John Gillingham, Henry and his reign have attracted historians for many years and Richard (whose reputation has "fluctuated wildly") is remembered largely because of his military exploits.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Interpretations of *Magna Carta* and the role of the rebel barons in 1215 have been revised; although the charter's symbolic, constitutional value for later generations is unquestionable, for most historians it is a failed peace agreement between factions.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] John's opposition to the papacy and his promotion of royal rights and prerogatives won favour from 16th-century Tudors.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] John Foxe, William Tyndale and Robert Barnes viewed John as an early Protestant hero, and Foxe included the king in his *Book of Martyrs*.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] John Speed's 1632 *Historie of Great Britaine* praised John's "great renown" as king, blaming biased medieval chroniclers for the king's poor reputation.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Similarly, later Protestant historians view Henry's role in Thomas Becket's death and his disputes with the French as worthy of praise.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Similarly, increased access to contemporary records during the late Victorian era led to a recognition of Henry's contributions to the evolution of English law and the exchequer.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] William Stubbs called Henry a "legislator king" because of his responsibility for major, long-term reforms in England; in contrast, Richard was "a bad son, a bad husband, a selfish ruler, and a vicious man".
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] The growth of the British Empire led historian Kate Norgate to begin detailed research into Henry's continental possessions and create the term "Angevin Empire" during the 1880s.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] However, 20th-century historians challenged many of these conclusions.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] During the 1950s, Jacques Boussard, John Jolliffe and others focused on the nature of Henry's "empire"; French scholars, in particular, analysed the mechanics of royal power during this period.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Anglocentric aspects of many histories of Henry's reign were challenged beginning in the 1980s, with efforts to unite British and French historical analyses of the period.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Detailed study of Henry's written records has cast doubt on earlier interpretations; Robert Eyton's 1878 volume (tracing Henry's itinerary by deductions from pipe rolls), for example, has been criticised for not acknowledging uncertainty.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Although many of Henry's royal charters have been identified, their interpretation, the financial information in the pipe rolls and broad economic data from his reign has proven more challenging than once thought.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Significant gaps in the historical analysis of Henry remain, particularly about his rule in Anjou and the south of France.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Interest in the morality of historical figures and scholars waxed during the Victorian period, leading to increased criticism of Henry's behaviour and Becket's death.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Historians relied on the judgement of chroniclers to focus on John's ethos.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Norgate wrote that John's downfall was due not to his military failures but his "almost superhuman wickedness", and James Ramsay blamed John's family background and innate cruelty for his downfall.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Richard's sexuality has been controversial since the 1940s, when John Harvey challenged what he saw as "the conspiracy of silence" surrounding the king's homosexuality with chronicles of Richard's behaviour, two public confessions, penances and childless marriage.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Opinion remains divided, with Gillingham arguing against Richard's homosexuality and Jean Flori acknowledging its possibility.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] According to recent biographers Ralph Turner and Lewis Warren, although John was an unsuccessful monarch, his failings were exaggerated by 12th- and 13th-century chroniclers.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Jim Bradbury echoes the contemporary consensus that John was a "hard-working administrator, an able man, an able general" with, as Turner suggests, "distasteful, even dangerous personality traits".
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] John Gillingham (author of a biography of Richard I) agrees and judges John to be a less-effective general than Turner and Warren do.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Bradbury takes a middle view, suggesting that modern historians have been overly lenient in evaluating John's flaws.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Popular historian Frank McLynn wrote that the king's modern reputation amongst historians is "bizarre" and, as a monarch, John "fails almost all those [tests] that can be legitimately set".
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Henry II appears as a fictionalised character in several modern plays and films.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] The king is a central character in James Goldman's play *The Lion in Winter* (1966), depicting an imaginary encounter between Henry's family and Philip Augustus over Christmas 1183 at Chinon.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Philip's strong character contrasts with John, an "effete weakling".
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] In the 1968 film, Henry is a sacrilegious, fiery and determined king.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Henry also appears in Jean Anouilh's play *Becket*, which was filmed in 1964.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Eliot's play *Murder in the Cathedral*, an exploration of Becket's death and Eliot's religious interpretation of it.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] During the Tudor period, popular representations of John emerged.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] He appeared as a "proto-Protestant martyr" in the anonymous play *The Troublesome Reign of King John* and John Bale's morality play *Kynge Johan*, in which John attempts to save England from the "evil agents of the Roman Church".Curren-Aquino 1989, p.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] 19 Shakespeare's anti-Catholic *King John* draws on *The Troublesome Reign*, offering a "balanced, dual view of a complex monarch as both a proto-Protestant victim of Rome's machinations and as a weak, selfishly motivated ruler".Curren-Aquino 1989, p.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] 19 Anthony Munday's plays *The Downfall and The Death of Robert Earl of Huntington* demonstrate many of John's negative traits, but approve of the king's stand against the Roman Catholic Church.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Richard is the subject of two operas: In 1719, George Frideric Handel used Richard's invasion of Cyprus as the plot for *Riccardo Primo*, and, in 1784, André Grétry wrote *Richard Coeur-de-lion*.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] The earliest ballads of Robin Hood such as those compiled in *A Gest of Robyn Hode* associated the character with a king named "Edward" and the setting is usually attributed by scholars to either the 13th or the 14th century.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Holt notes at some time around the 16th century, tales of Robin Hood started to mention him as a contemporary and supporter of Richard, Robin being driven to outlawry during John's misrule, while in the narratives Richard was largely absent, away at the Third Crusade.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Plays such as Robert Davenport's *King John and Matilda* further developed the Elizabethan works in the mid-17th century, focussing on John's tyranny and transferring the role of Protestant champion to the barons.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Graham Tulloch noted that unfavourable 19th-century fictionalised depictions of John were influenced by Sir Walter Scott's historical romance *Ivanhoe*.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] They, in turn, influenced the children's author Howard Pyle's *The Merry Adventures of Robin Hood* (1883) which cast John as the principal villain of the Robin Hood narrative.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] During the 20th century, John also appeared in fictional books and films with Robin Hood.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Sam De Grasse's John, in the 1922 film version, commits atrocities and acts of torture.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Claude Rains' John, in the 1938 version with Errol Flynn, began a cinematic trend in which John was an "effeminate ... arrogant and cowardly stay-at-home".
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] John's character highlights Richard's virtues and contrasts with Guy of Gisbourne, the "swashbuckling villain" opposing Robin.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] In the Disney cartoon version, John (voiced by Peter Ustinov) is a "cowardly, thumbsucking lion".
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] During the 13th century, a folktale developed in which Richard's minstrel Blondel roamed (singing a song known only to him and Richard) to find Richard's prison.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] This story was the foundation of André Ernest Modeste Grétry's opera *Richard Coeur-de-Lion*, and inspired the opening of Richard Thorpe's film version of *Ivanhoe*.
[src:clan-bruce/angevin-kings-of-england] Sixteenth-century tales of Robin Hood began describing him as a contemporary (and supporter) of Richard the Lionheart; Robin became an outlaw during the reign of Richard's evil brother, John, while Richard was fighting in the Third Crusade.
[src:clan-bruce/annandale-dumfries-and-galloway] Annandale is famous for its connection with Robert the Bruce, as the de Brus family was given this land by David I in 1124 as one of the border lordships when David became Prince of the Cumbrians.
[src:clan-bruce/annandale-dumfries-and-galloway] Along with Carrick, these lands acted as a buffer between the quasi-independent Lordship or Kingdom of Galloway and David's lands of Strathclyde and Cumbria.
[src:clan-bruce/clan-bruce] The surname *Bruce* comes from the French *de Brus* or *de Bruis*, derived from the lands now called *Brix*, Normandy, France.
[src:clan-bruce/clan-bruce] There is no evidence to support a claim that a member of the family, 'Robert de Brix', served under William the Conqueror during the Norman Conquest of England.
[src:clan-bruce/clan-bruce] This notion is now believed to have originated in unreliable lists, derived from the later Middle Ages, of people who supposedly fought at the Battle of Hastings.
[src:clan-bruce/clan-bruce] Both the English and Scots lines of the Brus/Bruce family demonstrably descend from Robert de Brus, 1st Lord of Annandale who came to England in 1106.
[src:clan-bruce/clan-bruce] Robert de Brus was a companion-in-arms of Prince David, later King David I.
[src:clan-bruce/clan-bruce] In 1124 he followed David north to reclaim his kingdom.
[src:clan-bruce/clan-bruce] When a civil war broke out in England between Empress Matilda and her cousin, Stephen, David I of Scotland led a force into England.
[src:clan-bruce/clan-bruce] However de Brus did not follow David and instead joined the English and at the Battle of the Standard in 1138 he took prisoner his own son, who was now Lord of the lands of Annandale.
[src:clan-bruce/clan-bruce] Robert de Brus, 1st Lord of Annandale died on 11 May 1141 and was buried at Gysburn.
[src:clan-bruce/clan-bruce] The foundation for the Bruce royal claim came in 1219 when Robert Bruce, 4th Lord of Annandale married Isobel of Huntingdon, daughter of David of Scotland, 8th Earl of Huntingdon and niece of William the Lion.
[src:clan-bruce/clan-bruce] The union brought both great wealth, with the addition of lands in both England and Scotland.
[src:clan-bruce/clan-bruce] Their son, Robert Bruce, 5th Lord of Annandale, known as "The Competitor" was sometime Tanist (a particularly Gaelic type of heir) to the throne.
[src:clan-bruce/clan-bruce] On the death of Alexander III both Bruce and John Balliol claimed succession.
[src:clan-bruce/clan-bruce] Margaret, Alexander's infant granddaughter was named as heir, however, she died in 1290 travelling to Scotland to claim her throne.
[src:clan-bruce/clan-bruce] Soon after the death of young queen Margaret, fearing civil war between the Bruce and Balliol families and their supporters, the Guardians of Scotland asked the kingdom's southern neighbour, Edward I of England to arbitrate among the claimants in order to avoid civil war.
[src:clan-bruce/clan-bruce] Edward I saw this as the opportunity he had long been waiting for to conquer Scotland as he had conquered Wales and rule over all the British Isles.
[src:clan-bruce/clan-bruce] In 1292 Edward chose Balliol who swore allegiance to the English monarch.
[src:clan-bruce/clan-bruce] It was not long, however, before Balliol rebelled against Edward, eventually leading to John's defeat and forced abdication after the Battle of Dunbar in 1296.
[src:clan-bruce/clan-bruce] With the abdication of John Balliol, Scotland was effectively without a monarch.
[src:clan-bruce/clan-bruce] Robert the Bruce swore allegiance to Edward at Berwick-upon-Tweed but breached this oath when he joined the Scottish revolt the following year.
[src:clan-bruce/clan-bruce] In the summer of 1297 he again swore allegiance to Edward in what is known as the Capitulation of Irvine.
[src:clan-bruce/clan-bruce] Bruce appears to have sided with the Scots during the Battle of Stirling Bridge but when Edward returned victorious to England after the Battle of Falkirk, Bruce's lands of Annandale and Carrick were exempted from the lordships and lands which Edward assigned to his followers.
[src:clan-bruce/clan-bruce] Bruce, it seems, was seen as a man whose allegiance might still be won.
[src:clan-bruce/clan-bruce] Bruce and John Comyn (a rival for the throne) succeeded William Wallace as Guardians of Scotland, but their rivalry threatened the stability of the country.
[src:clan-bruce/clan-bruce] A meeting was arranged at Greyfriars Church, Dumfries which was neutral ground, but Bruce stabbed Comyn through the heart, and as a result was excommunicated by Pope Clement V.
[src:clan-bruce/clan-bruce] Nevertheless, Robert the Bruce was crowned King of Scotland at Scone, Perthshire in 1306.
[src:clan-bruce/clan-bruce] However, soon after he was forced by the English to retreat into Argyll, in an attempt to reach his Clan Campbell allies.
[src:clan-bruce/clan-bruce] The Clan MacDougall, whose chief was the uncle or cousin of John Comyn who Bruce had murdered, surprised the Bruce and defeated him in what was known as the Battle of Dalrigh.
[src:clan-bruce/clan-bruce] The king escaped but left behind what was described as a magnificent example of Celtic jewellery, known as the *Brooch of Lorne* and it became one of the Clan MacDougall's great treasures.
[src:clan-bruce/clan-bruce] Three years later Robert the Bruce led three thousand battle hardened veterans into Argyll against the MacDougalls.
[src:clan-bruce/clan-bruce] John MacDougall of Lorne set an ambush for them but in the ensuing Battle of the Pass of Brander the MacDougalls were defeated and forced to flee.
[src:clan-bruce/clan-bruce] The MacDougalls' lands were then forfeited by the king and he gave them to the Campbells for their loyalty.
[src:clan-bruce/clan-bruce] Robert the Bruce led the Scottish army at the Battle of Bannockburn in 1314 where the English were defeated.
[src:clan-bruce/clan-bruce] In 1334 Thomas Bruce, who claimed kinship with the royal house of Bruce, organized a rising in the Kyle, along with Robert Stewart (later King Robert II) against the English.
[src:clan-bruce/clan-bruce] Robert the Bruce's son, David II became king on his father's death in 1329.
[src:clan-bruce/clan-bruce] In 1346 under the terms of the Auld Alliance David marched south into England in the interests of France, but was defeated at the Battle of Neville's Cross and imprisoned on 17 October of that year, and remained in England for eleven years.
[src:clan-bruce/clan-bruce] David returned to Scotland after negotiation of a treaty and ruled there until he died in Edinburgh Castle unexpectedly in 1371 without issue.
[src:clan-bruce/clan-bruce] The line of succession passed to the House of Stewart.
[src:clan-bruce/clan-bruce] Sir Edward Bruce was made commendator of Kinloss Abbey, which included the Barony of Muirton, and was appointed a judge in 1597.
[src:clan-bruce/clan-bruce] He was appointed a Lord of Parliament with the title of Lord Kinloss in 1601.
[src:clan-bruce/clan-bruce] Edward Bruce accompanied James VI to claim his English throne in 1603.
[src:clan-bruce/clan-bruce] As a result, he was subsequently appointed to English judicial office as Master of the Rolls.
[src:clan-bruce/clan-bruce] He was granted the Barony of Kinloss as Lord Bruce of Kinloss in 1608.
[src:clan-bruce/clan-bruce] In 1633 his son, Thomas, was created first Earl of Elgin.
[src:clan-bruce/clan-bruce] When the fourth Earl died without issue, the title passed to the descendants of Sir George Bruce of Carnock, who already held the title Earl of Kincardine and in 1747 the Earldoms were united.
[src:clan-bruce/clan-bruce] Thomas Bruce, 7th Earl of Elgin was a diplomat and ambassador to the Ottoman Empire between 1799 and 1803.
[src:clan-bruce/clan-bruce] He spent much of his fortune collecting marble sculptures from the Parthenon in Athens, after receiving a permission from the Ottoman Empire.
[src:clan-bruce/clan-bruce] They are now commonly referred to as the Elgin Marbles.
[src:clan-bruce/clan-bruce] His son, James, was Governor General of the Province of Canada and Viceroy of India.
[src:clan-bruce/clan-bruce] The current Chief, Andrew Bruce, 11th Earl of Elgin, is prominent in Scottish affairs and is convenor of the Standing Council of Scottish Chiefs.
